      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":70,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":353,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":353,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at the relaxed end of easy pace — conversational, no effort. Let your body ease into the run.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":338,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable aerobic rhythm. You should be able to speak in full sentences throughout.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Back off to your most relaxed pace. Focus on form and breathing as you finish.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk for 2–3 minutes before you start running to let your joints warm up, especially on Monday after a rest day.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5 minutes of light walking and dynamic stretching — hip circles, leg swings, calf raises.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your foundation run — pure aerobic development. At 5:08–5:53/km you're building mitochondrial density and fat-burning efficiency without accumulating fatigue. Monday's easy run sets the tone for the week. Keep it genuinely easy; the temptation to push on a fresh Monday is real but resisting it pays dividends by Sunday.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Marathon Pace Progression Run\",\"target_distance_km\":14,\"target_duration_minutes\":72,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":338,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":272,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy conversational pace for the first 3 km. Let your body rehearse good form before the work begins.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":42,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":272,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Hold 4:32/km — your goal marathon pace. This should feel controlled and purposeful, not labored. Think 'comfortably hard.' You are teaching your body what race day feels like.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog back to full recovery. Don't skip this — it clears lactate and reinforces the aerobic adaptation you just stimulated.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 km easy jog at 5:08–5:53/km before transitioning to marathon pace. Use the warmup to check in with how your body feels today.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3 km easy cooldown jog. Follow with standing hip flexor stretch and calf stretches held for 30 seconds each side.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This Wednesday workout is the backbone of your marathon build. Running at exactly 4:32/km teaches your body to sustain race-day effort efficiently — it improves lactate clearance at pace, reinforces your fueling strategy, and builds mental familiarity with the effort you'll need on September 5. A 3:15 marathon requires consistent comfort at this pace, so we're building that relationship now. Keep the easy bookends genuinely easy — the contrast between them and the marathon pace segment is part of the stimulus.\",\"perceived_effort\":6},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2max Cruise Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":13,\"target_duration_minutes\":75,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":338,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":236,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy 3 km jog. Include 4–6 strides of 20 seconds at interval pace in the final 5 minutes to prime your neuromuscular system before the hard work.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":236,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 × 1000m at 3:56/km with 90-second easy jog recovery between each. This pace should feel hard but controlled — you can say a few words but not hold a conversation. Do not go faster; the recovery is part of the prescription.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"90 seconds of easy jogging between each interval. Use this time to relax your shoulders and reset your form before the next rep.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy 3 km jog cooldown. This is non-negotiable — your cardiovascular system needs time to transition back to rest.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 km easy jog followed by 4–6 × 20-second strides at interval pace (3:56/km) with full recovery between each. Strides prime your fast-twitch fibers and make the transition into interval pace feel more natural.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3 km easy jog. Follow with 10 minutes of static stretching — quads, hamstrings, hip flexors, calves. Hydrate well.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals at 3:56/km are one of the highest-leverage sessions in marathon training. They raise your aerobic ceiling — the faster your VO2max, the more comfortable marathon pace feels as a percentage of your maximum. Five 1000m reps with 90-second recovery is a classic Jack Daniels prescription: enough stimulus to drive adaptation without accumulating the kind of fatigue that would compromise Sunday's long run. The key is discipline — hold 3:56/km and no faster. Going out too hard on rep 1 is the most common mistake here.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run with Marathon Pace Finish\",\"target_distance_km\":24,\"target_duration_minutes\":138,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":353,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":272,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at your most comfortable easy pace — the slow end of 5:08–5:53/km. You have a long morning ahead; there is no benefit to starting faster.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":108,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":338,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run the first 18 km at easy pace (5:08–5:30/km). This builds your aerobic base and fat oxidation capacity. Stay well fueled — take a gel or equivalent at km 8 and km 16.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":272,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 4–5 km at marathon pace (4:32/km). Running at race pace on tired legs is one of the most race-specific adaptations you can build. It trains your body to hold form and pace when glycogen is partially depleted — exactly what the final 10 km of a marathon demands.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":353,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final km at easy pace to bring your heart rate down before stopping. Never stop abruptly after a long effort.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start walking for 3–5 minutes before your run if you're heading out on cold legs. The long run doesn't need a formal warmup — the first 3 km serve that purpose naturally at easy pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes after finishing. Follow with thorough stretching: 30 seconds each of standing quad stretch, seated hamstring stretch, pigeon pose, and calf stretch. Eat and hydrate within 30 minutes of finishing to support recovery before the work week begins.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The Sunday long run is the cornerstone of marathon preparation. At 24 km this week, you're holding your current long run distance — appropriate given this is an early base-building week and we don't want to spike your weekly volume unnecessarily. The marathon-pace finish (final 4–5 km at 4:32/km) is the secret weapon of this session: it teaches your legs what race effort feels like when fatigued, builds mental resilience, and improves your glycogen efficiency at pace. Take your fueling seriously on this run — practice exactly what you plan to do on race day in terms of timing and product. Sunday's run is also about confidence: finishing strong on tired legs tells your body and your mind that 3:15 is within reach.\",\"perceived_effort\":7}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
